Calculating the Maclaurin expansion we find that

\begin{align*}\left(e^{At}\right)^{H} = \left(\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\frac{(At)^{k}}{k!}\right)^{H} = \sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\frac{(A^{H}t)^{k}}{k!}=e^{\left(A^{H}\right)t}\end{align*}

Thus,

\begin{align*}\left(e^{At}\right)^{H} e^{At}=\left(e^{A^{H}t}\right)e^{At}=\left(e^{-At}\right)e^{At}=e^{0}=I.\end{align*}
